# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eugene-allen-smith
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The **33rd Alabama Infantry Regiment** was an infantry unit from Alabama that served in the Confederate States Army during the U.S.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Recruited from the southeastern counties of Butler, Dale, Coffee, Covington, Russell and Montgomery, it saw extensive service with the Confederate Army of Tennessee before being nearly annihilated at the Battle of Franklin in 1864.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Survivors from the regiment continued to serve until the final capitulation of General Joseph Johnston in North Carolina in 1865.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Initially assigned to the defense of Confederate forts in Pensacola Bay, Florida, the 33rd was quickly transferred to duty in the Army of Tennessee, where it saw its first significant action at the Battle of Perryville.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] It went on to fight at Stone's River, Chickamauga, the Siege of Chattanooga, the Atlanta campaign (including Ringgold Gap and Kennesaw Mountain), and the disastrous Franklin-Nashville Campaign in late 1864.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] From just after the Battle of Perryville through the Battle of Franklin, the 33rd fought under the "Stonewall of the West": Major General Patrick Cleburne, an Irish-born officer whom General Robert E.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Lee once referred to as "a meteor shining from a clouded sky" for his battlefield prowess.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Though it took horrific losses at Perryville (where it suffered eighty-two percent casualties) and at Franklin (where it lost two-thirds of its numbers), it held together with reduced numbers until the final Carolina Campaign in 1865.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Historians of the 33rd benefit from extremely detailed accounts of this regiment's service by soldiers who served in it; the most important of these was written by Private W.E.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] B, who left records of nearly every aspect of regimental life from food to clothing to nicknames, sundries and even the soldiers' opinions of two different service rifles they were issued.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The 33rd Alabama Infantry Regiment was organized in April 1862, in Pensacola, Florida.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The 33rd Alabama was initially assigned to duty during March–April 1862 at Fort McRee, which sat at the entrance to Pensacola Bay, Florida, opposite the Federal-held Fort Pickens.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] McRee had been reduced to near-rubble by Federal warships and the guns of Ft.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] However, the local commander, General Braxton Bragg, insisted on holding it, anyway.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] According to one veteran's memoirs, their time at this location was spent in initial military training, drill, and guard duty.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] At one point, local commanders decided to remove the coastal artillery from the badly damaged fortress, and the 33rd was asked to help.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The guns were removed from their five- to eight-inch bases during daylight hours; later, at night, they were slung beneath a specially built wagon equipped with fourteen-inch-wide tires, to which thirty-six mules were hitched.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] A lengthy rope was tied to the tongue, and 100 soldiers were tasked with pulling on it to help these mules haul the cannon across the sandy beach to barges on the bay, which in turn carried them on to Pensacola.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The guns were replaced with wood planks shaped and painted to resemble artillery, to deceive the Federals into thinking the fort—or what was left of it at this point—was still a threat.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] McRee, the regiment had its first direct encounter with the enemy—or what it *thought* was the enemy, at the time.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] During a fierce rainstorm one night, a Federal ship endeavoring to resupply Ft.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Private Matthews reported engaging a "whaleboat full of Yankees" trying to salvage some of these supplies; apparently, little damage was done by either side.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Following their initial duty at Pensacola, the 33rd was ordered to report to Corinth, Mississippi, for duty with General Albert Sidney Johnston's Army of Mississippi.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Arriving just after the Confederate loss at Shiloh (in which Johnston was killed and replaced in command by General P.G.T.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Beauregard), the 33rd was assigned to the brigade commanded by Colonel Alexander T.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Hawthorn, which was part of the Army's 3rd Corps.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] In July 1862 Hawthorn's brigade became part of a division commanded by Major General William Hardee, and the following month the 33rd was transferred to a brigade (still in Hardee's division) commanded by Brigadier General Sterling Wood.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Private Matthews reported being "strung out in muddy ditches in S.A.M.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] When General Hardee was given command of the "Left Wing" of the Army of Mississippi (now commanded by General Bragg, from the 33rd's Pensacola days), Wood's Fourth Brigade was assigned to the Third Division of the Left Wing, under command of Major General Simon Bolivar Buckner.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] In concert with the rest of the army, the 33rd left Corinth at the end of July and travelled by train from Tupelo, Mississippi, to Meridian; thence to Mobile, Alabama, and Montgomery, then on to Atlanta, Georgia, and Dalton before arriving at Tyner's Station, just east of Chattanooga, Tennessee.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Following this, Wood's brigade marched into the city, where they crossed the Tennessee River on "a ferry boat, propelled by two blind horses" while picking up two months' pay (at $11 per month), a $50 bounty for each soldier, new shoes and clothing, and rations.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Up to now, the 33rd had not seen any significant action, but this was about to change.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Pursuing Federal troops rounded up many stragglers, but refrained from attacking the main Confederate force at first.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Bragg's army reached the fortified town of Munfordville, on the Green River, on September 14.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Despite the huge advantage in numbers possessed by the Southerners, the Federal commander, Colonel John T.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Wilder, refused the initial demand for surrender.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Confederate forces attacked his works and were repulsed, settling in for a two-day siege before the Federal commander was finally persuaded to give up after being taken on a personal tour of the Confederate siege lines by General Buckner.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Following a Confederate victory at Richmond, Kentucky on August 30, Confederate forces advanced deeper into that state, seeking to drive the Federals across the Ohio River and thus establish the Confederacy's northern boundary on that waterway.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Desperate for water, both armies converged on the tiny village of Perryville, Kentucky, where water was said to still be available.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The Confederates reached the town first, with the 33rd Alabama arriving around 10:00 am on the morning of October 7 and deploying with the rest of Wood's brigade to the north of town.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] A battle commenced on the morning of October 8, with the 33rd taking little part until late afternoon, when Bragg called for fresh troops to launch an attack on Dixville Crossroads, held by the 34th Federal Brigade under Colonel George Webster.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Webster's brigade contained the 22nd Indiana, 75th Illinois and 59th Illinois Infantry regiments, all of whom were raw recruits who had never seen combat before.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Wood's brigade, including the 33rd Alabama, attacked around 5pm and ran into murderous fire from Webster's men.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The Federals, supported by Captain Harris' battery, decimated the attacking Confederates and forced them to withdraw.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Regrouping at the base of the hill, the 33rd and its sister regiments—now assisting a fresh brigade led by Brigadier General St.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] John Richardson Liddell—charged again, taking more casualties but ultimately driving the Federals from the hill after Harris' battery ran out of ammunition and was forced to withdraw.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The 22nd Indiana, directly opposite the 33rd Alabama, suffered 65% casualties—the most of any Federal unit on the battlefield.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] When the smoke finally cleared that evening, the Confederates had won a tactical victory at Perryville.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] However the approach of fresh Union forces and the increasingly untenable situation in Kentucky compelled Bragg to order a retreat.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The 33rd and the rest of Bragg's army withdrew to Tennessee through the Cumberland Gap, leaving the Federals in possession of Kentucky for the rest of the war.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] During the Battle of Perryville, the 33rd Alabama suffered an appalling casualty rate of 82%.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Entering the battle with 500 men,d the regiment came out with only 88 fit for duty.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Of the thirty-two men in the 33rd's Company B who fought at Perryville, two were killed on the field and nineteen more were wounded—of whom only nine survived.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] After the battle, Private Matthews reported that the surviving members of the regiment carried their injured comrades to field hospitals, while others removed the personal effects from the dead to return to their families in Alabama.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] He reports that though exhausted from the day's fighting, the surviving troops spent all that night carrying water to their friends, gathering straw for them to lie on, and assisting the surgeons in caring for them.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] When some of the wounded complained of being cold, their comrades covered them with their own blankets.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Upon returning to their camp later on, the survivors discovered that their left-behind knapsacks had been plundered by persons unknown.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Matthews also related the account of a mortally wounded soldier named Ward who asked his "body servant"e Jesse to return to Alabama and convey his final goodbye to his wife.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Matthews emphasized that Jesse could easily have run away in the confusion and sought freedom with nearby Federal troops, but he chose to return home—entirely on his own—carrying his master's message.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] While fragging—the assassination of unpopular officers by their subordinates—is generally associated with the Vietnam War, incidents of this nature occurred during the Civil War as well.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Although they did not manage to murder him, they were overjoyed to learn of Keep's departure after the battle.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] After withdrawing from Perryville, General Bragg moved south toward Harrodsburg, Kentucky, where he linked up with another Confederate force under Major General Kirby Smith.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] From here he continued his retreat to Knoxville, Tennessee, where the army drew supplies described as: "flour, corn meal, bacon, fresh beef, rice, salt and the first soap that we had drawn in two months," together with new uniforms and shoes.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Here the regiment was rejoined by several previously ill soldiers, who had been left behind at hospitals in Chattanooga at the outset of the Kentucky Campaign.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] On November 4, 1862, the 33rd Alabama was ordered to board a train which was scheduled to take them to Chattanooga.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] In a freak accident a few miles south of Cleveland, Tennessee, a large stick of wood fell from the locomotive tender as the train moved rapidly on a downhill grade, breaking the axle of one of the railcars immediately behind it and causing part of the train to derail.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Matthews reports that when the axle snapped on the boxcar he was in, all the wheels came off and "clogged" under the wheels of the car behind it (occupied by Co.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] G), causing its separation from the train.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Meanwhile, the engine continued to pull the wheel-less B Company car two or three hundred yards down the track before it finally stopped.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] A total of seventeen men were killed in the disaster, with sixty-seven others maimed; many of these later died from their injuries.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] G, the "Daleville Blues," including the company commander, Captain Reuben Jackson Cooper.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] All were buried the next day in a trench dug just southeast of the railroad that was surrounded by a split-rail fence; this remained unmarked and largely forgotten until descendants of the departed erected a monument on the site in November 1989.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Following the Battle of Perryville, the 33rd Alabama—together with the rest of Wood's brigade—was transferred to a new division commanded by Major General Patrick R.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Cleburne, under whom the 33rd served for most of the rest of the war.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] By now Bragg had converted his "wings" into corps; Cleburne's division was assigned to the corps commanded by Lieutenant General William J.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Hardee, in what was now officially called the Army of Tennessee.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] After leaving Chattanooga, General Bragg and his army moved west until they reached the small town of Murfreesboro, Tennessee, 35 miles (56 km) southeast of Union-held Nashville.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Private Matthews reports that the 33rd Alabama was tasked to serve as a rear guard for their brigade along the line of march, occasionally skirmishing with pursuing Federal forces while contending with muddy roads during the final portion of their journey.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Knowing that Murfreesboro and the surrounding area were staunchly pro-Southern in sentiment, Bragg felt compelled to make a stand on relatively flat ground north of the city, even though several more-defensible areas lay further to the north and south.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The Federal Army of the Cumberland, now under the command of Major General William S.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Rosecrans, closed with Bragg in late December 1862, arriving at Murfreesboro on December 29 and moving into position the following day.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Following a musical contest between Southern and Federal bands during the evening hours on the 30th, both armies prepared to attack each other at dawn on the 31st.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Incredibly, Bragg and Rosecrans had each made plans to assault each other's right flank, at almost the same moment.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Hardee's corps—more than 10,000 troops in all— attacked at dawn in a massive wave, hoping to catch their enemy off guard and preoccupied with eating breakfast and other morning activities, just as they had done at Shiloh where they had achieved complete surprise.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] A ration of whiskey was issued to the troops at 8:00 pm; soon afterwards they bedded down for the night, sleeping on cornstalks in an effort to keep off the soggy ground.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Private Matthews reported that when the battle first commenced, haze had obscured the field so much that visibility was limited to about fifty feet.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] He reported that during the initial charge, the Federals abandoned their "breakfast[s] on the fire," together with tents, wagons, knapsacks, foodstuffs and other supplies.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Blaming "inferior powder" for causing many of their Enfield rifles to fail at Perryville and now here, he indicates that most of his comrades threw away those weapons in favor of Federal Springfield Model 1861 rifles they found on the battlefield.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Matthews equally writes that many soldiers were trading in their original-issue cedar canteens (from their Ft.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] McRee days) for the "cloth covered, block tin oval shaped Yankee canteen[s]" they found.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Federal blankets, shelter halves, hats (which Matthews described as "good") and overcoats were also prized by the 33rd Alabama—those who could not find them on the field, would purchase them from others who had extras.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Stones River ended on January 2, 1863, as a Federal victory: though Bragg had inflicted severe losses on Rosecrans' army, he had been unable to drive it from the field.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] With fresh Union reinforcements threatening to give Rosecrans an overwhelming advantage for a future attack, Bragg chose to retreat to Tullahoma, Tennessee.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] During the 33rd's time in Tullahoma, several members of Company I (from Dale County) contracted smallpox, apparently from a soldier who had been on furlough to Columbus, Georgia.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The entire regiment was ordered into quarantine, which entailed moving away from the rest of the army and into a nearby creek swamp, where they established camp on high ground and waited out the epidemic.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Those who died there were buried in the swamp by other members of their mess, but were not accorded the military honors usually given to those who died in camp or in battle.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Once this enforced isolation was revoked, The 33rd celebrated by taking the offensive in an entirely new kind of war.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] After being removed from quarantine, the regiment witnessed the hanging of a Federal spy, then moved on to Wartrace, where they went into camp for a time.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Although the 33rd was taking a rest at Wartrace, not all of its time was spent leisurely.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Its new divisional commander, General Cleburne, drilled his men and held marksmanship competitions together with frequent readiness and equipment inspections.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Cleburne's previous record of success went over well with his new troops; he insisted on weapons being clean and well-maintained at all times, and also that his soldiers attend to their own personal hygiene to the best extent possible.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] A new blue-and-white regimental flag was issued, with "Perryville" and "Murfreesboro" written on it in large white letters, the original one having been virtually destroyed at those two engagements.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Other jolly souls sang songs, especially at night; others played various games of chance: cards, dice, kino or other games.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] We ... fished in creeks or rivers or went in bathing, and some frequently attended religious services ...
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Matthews reports that Wartrace was the last place where his regiment used the wall tents they had been issued at the beginning of their service.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Once they left there, he says, the tents were either "captured or burned." A sergeant assigned to the unit managed to abscond with all the pocketwatches in the regiment, whereupon he promptly deserted to the Federals.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Early in 1863, the 33rd Alabama learned that a battalion of partisan rangers from Jackson County, Alabama, in the northern part of the state, was being "attached" to them for administrative and command purposes, without losing its identity.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Recruited in the summer of 1862, the 1st Partisan Rangers Battalion was originally mounted and intended for local service.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Composed of five companies that were later consolidated into three, the 18th was attached to the 33rd Alabama in January 1863 (after previously serving under General Nathan Bedford Forrest) and fought with the 33rd thereafter, while still remaining a separate organization.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Gibson, it was also known as Gibson's Battalion.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] On June 24, 1863, the Federal Army of the Cumberland opened its Tullahoma Campaign in central Tennessee.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] This lasted until July 3, and resulted in Bragg's dislodgement from strong defensive positions at Tullahoma and nearby areas including Wartrace.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Hearing the Federals open fire on the 24th, the 33rd Alabama cooked three days' rations of flour, beef, bacon and corn meal, then marched back to the main army at Tullahoma, which was evacuated around June 30.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Bragg moved south toward Chattanooga, a strategically valuable city that was considered the "gateway" to Georgia and its vital railway center of Atlanta.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Halting at a big spring just outside the town of Harrison, Tennessee, the 33rd was initially ordered to guard the river crossings at this point.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] In September, the regiment was ordered to evacuate this position, and moved into Chattanooga.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Having forced Bragg to evacuate Chattanooga on September 6 through a series of skillful maneuvers, Rosecrans ordered his army to advance along three different roads into northwestern Georgia in pursuit of the Army of Tennessee.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] With the Federals divided and unable to support each other due to the mountainous terrain, Bragg chose to concentrate on one Union corps, the XIV Corps, which had advanced through the same gap taken by the 33rd at Pigeon Mountain (and adjacent passes), and was moving toward Lafayette.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] An abortive assault launched by Cleyburne's and Hindman's divisions at Davis's Cross Roads allowed the Federals to escape to safety, so Bragg now turned north, where Rosecran's main force was rapidly concentrating at Lee and Gordon's Mill along Chickamauga Creek.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Having been promised three extra divisions—including two led by the renowned Lieutenant General James Longstreet—Bragg decided to attack Rosecrans' army.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Skirmishing commenced on September 18, with the main battle opening on September 19.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] This engagement marked one of the very few major contests of the war in which the Confederate force outnumbered the Federals: 65,000 to 60,000.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Bragg's plan was for the Confederates to push past the Federals at Chickamauga Creek, then move north toward Chattanooga.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] If executed correctly, this maneuver would force Rosecrans to give battle against superior numbers under unfavorable conditions, or to withdraw.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Unfortunately for Bragg things did not go exactly as he had intended, and by the afternoon of the 19th his forces were strung out along a densely wooded battlefront roughly 5 miles (8.0 km) in length.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] With the Federals putting up a terrific fight and showing no disposition to give way, Bragg ordered the 33rd Alabama and the rest of Cleburne's division (which had been on the left side of his army up to this point) to move north to the Youngblood Farm, near the far right flank.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Though most of the fighting had shifted further south over the course of the afternoon, Bragg understood that the main effort had to come at the opposite end of the field if he was to win.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] He still believed he could turn the Federal flank in the north, thereby obtaining control over the Lafayette Road and positioning himself between the Federals and Chattanooga, which was his key objective.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Wading Chickamauga creek after stripping off their shoes, pants and socks, the 33rd Alabama reached the Youngblood farm around 5:30 pm.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] After reporting to General Polk, Cleburne expected to be ordered to bed his men down for the evening, as night combat was extremely rare during the Civil War.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] However, to his immense astonishment, Cleburne received orders to form his troops into line in the fading light, and prepare to launch an immediate assault on the Federals to his front.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The 33rd Alabama and the rest of Wood's Brigade took center position in the attack formation, with Polk's Brigade to their right, and Deshler's brigade to their left.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Cleburne began his advance at 6:00 pm, through a tiny meadow locally known as Winfrey Field.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] This plot was described as being "200-300 yards in depth, and long enough to nearly cover the length of his brigade.".
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The 18th Alabama advanced to the left of the 33rd, while the 16th Alabama and the 45th, 32nd and 15th Mississippi regiments advanced to its right.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Three artillery batteries were placed in support, though in the gathering darkness they had potential to inflict as much damage on their friends as on the enemy.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] This enemy consisted of the 5th Kentucky, 1st Ohio and 32nd Indiana Infantry Regiments (belonging to Baldwin's and Willich's brigades of the Federal Army), who awaited them just behind a split rail fence near the treeline.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The 33rd and its sisters advanced cautiously toward the Federals, who quickly opened up on them from the far side of the field.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] At one point about halfway across, the 16th Alabama suddenly halted; Adams ordered the 33rd to stop, as well.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The two regiments resumed their advance after about ten minutes or so, though in the darkness they now had to deal with stragglers firing on them from behind, as well as the enemy to their front.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] One incident of friendly fire claimed the life of Lieutenant Alfred Mooreg, who was accidentally shot in the neck from behind by a straggler.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] A few companies of the 33rd began to waver, but Adams quickly corralled them and got them back into the fight.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] With the attack now stalling, artillery batteries were brought up in the darkness together with supporting troops under Brigadier General John Jackson; these finally drove the Federals back.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The 33rd Alabama crossed the Federal breastworks, heading straight for the nearby 6th Indiana.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] At this point, with their assault on the verge of success, the commander of the 16th Alabama suddenly ordered his regiment to retreat, upon which they scampered back toward the safety of their own lines.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Even though his left flank was now exposed, Colonel Adams chose to close with the 6th Indiana in the pitch-dark woods, where savage hand-to-hand fighting ensued before the Hoosiers finally withdrew.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Winfrey Field caught fire behind them from the artillery blasts, though the Rebel shells were mostly sailing over the defenders' heads.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Friendly units were now firing into each other in the darkness, lit up only by muzzle flashes and the blaze in the field, which threatened to consume the wounded of each army who lay there.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Mass confusion quickly set in on both sides, and although the Confederates achieved some success their attack ultimately ground to a halt, leaving the Federals in control of La Fayette Road.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Several men from the regiment had failed to remove their ramrods from their rifles as they fired them during the engagement; according to Matthews, these were stuck in trees as high as twenty feet above the ground; others were buried partway in the soil.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Miscommunication between General Bragg and his subordinates, together with blunders by General Polk, relegated the 33rd and its sister regiments to a series of futile assaults on the Federal left flank on September 20.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] At 7:25 that morning, as his men were eating breakfast, Cleburne received orders from Polk to attack the Federal line in a new location known as Kelly Field, in conjunction with troops of Brigadier General John C.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Breckinridge, a former Vice President of the United States who had sided with the South.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Wood's brigade had become tangled with Stewart's division (part of Longstreet's "wing" of the army), and none of the attackers or their officers realized that they were charging directly into six Federal divisions.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] General Wood's brigade became separated from the other attacking units, and quickly found itself on its own, attacking the Federals on high ground against overwhelming odds.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The 33rd Alabama began its advance about 10:00 am, in conjunction with the nearby 16th Alabama.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The latter regiment quickly took cover after the first volley from the Union line, while the 33rd continued to advance until they reached a small ravine, where they sheltered for nearly an hour until ordered to move forward again.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The two regiments now moved to a point about 275 yards from the Union line, when the 33rd was suddenly hit with murderous artillery and rifle fire from its right flank.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Completely bereft of support from either side, the 33rd continued to advance, ultimately achieving something no other Confederate regiment in that sector managed to do: it crossed the La Fayette Road, General Bragg's main objective.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] However, it was forced to retreat almost as soon as it had done so, having lost 16 killed and 133 wounded out of the 219 men who had started the assault.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Confusion and miscommunication were not confined to the Southern forces.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] A botched order issued by General Rosecrans opened a large gap in another part of the Federal line: Longstreet quickly exploited it, turning the Federal right flank and crippling their defense.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Rosecrans and most of his army fled the field, and only a desperate last-minute stand by Major General George H.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Thomas saved the Union army from complete annihilation.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The 33rd Alabama took part in a renewed assault on Kelly Field late in the afternoon, but due to its diminished numbers, it played little appreciable role in the final rout of Federal forces in that sector.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The Federals retreated all the way back to Chattanooga, where they awaited an immediate attack by Bragg's exultant army.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Bragg, however, threw away the greatest victory in his career by dallying on the battlefield to collect left-behind equipment and tend to his wounded, rather than quickly pursuing and destroying the demoralized Federals.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Upon reaching Chattanooga, Rosecrans' army quickly improved upon previous Confederate fortifications there; this ensured their survival and the ultimate defeat of Bragg's forces.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] The final casualty for the 33rd Alabama at Chickamauga was their longtime brigade commander, Brigadier General Wood.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Never mentioned in Cleburne's or anyone else's after-action reports, his performance during the assault at Winfrey Field remains shrouded in controversy.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p01] Privately accused of cowardace in the face of the enemy, and reportedly threatened with a court-martial by Cleburne, Wood resigned his commission soon after the battle ended, and returned to his law practice in Alabama.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Following the debacle at Chickamauga and his subsequent failure to prevent the routed Union forces from escaping to Chattanooga, Bragg placed that city under siege after hearing that his foes had just six days of food remaining.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Entrenching his forces atop Lookout Mountain and Missionary Ridge overlooking the city and the Tennessee River, Bragg soon learned that he would be facing a new opponent: Ulysses S.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Fresh from his victory at Vicksburg, Grant had been ordered to take command of all Federal forces in the region; his first action upon arriving was to remove Rosecrans and replace him with George Thomas, who had saved the Union army at Chickamauga.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The 33rd Alabama dug in on the west end of Missionary Ridge on November 22, behind a vineyard at its base.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Rifle pits were built, and guards rotated there every 24 hours; those not on guard duty set to work clearing all the vegetation from the west slope of the ridge, chopping the trees so that the tops fell toward Chattanooga, creating a natural barrier of tangled tree limbs.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Matthews reports that the removal of these trees allowed the cold autumn breezes to chill the troops on the ridge, since the Southerners had nothing but small tents to break the wind.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] At this point, Bragg chose to divide his army: Longstreet's 4,000 soldiers were ordered to move north to Knoxville to deal with a separate Federal force there under Ambrose Burnside.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] On November 22, he ordered General Cleburne to take his division, including the 33rd Alabama, together with another division under General Simon B.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Having successfully lifted the Siege of Chattanooga, General Grant now resolved on a double envelopment of Bragg's army.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The 33rd Alabama, entrenched atop the south end of Missionary Ridge near Bragg's headquarters, heard the sounds of battle on Lookout Mountain, but could not see the action due to a dense fog that had enveloped it.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Lowrey's brigade, including the 33rd, dug in to the south of the tunnel, but "only skirmishing" took place on that day.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Ordered to attack at dawn on November 25, General Sherman delayed until about 7am, when he sent his skirmishers forward.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The real attack did not begin until sometime between 10 and 10:30 am.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] With other units moving onto the ridge to his left, Cleburne shifted Lowrey's Brigade to a spur projecting from the ridge, just north of the tunnel.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Advancing into murderous fire, the Federals came to within eighty yards of the Southern positions before a furious Confederate counterattack forced them back, leading Sherman to call off the attack.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Cleburne indicated that the brunt of the battle was borne by Smith's Texas Brigade and three Arkansas regiments in Gowan's Brigade; the 33rd Alabama saw "heavy skirmishing," but did not play a major role since the Federals never approached closer than 100-200 yards to their sector of the line.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Cleburne's men had done their job, capturing eight enemy flags and 500 prisoners.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Further south along the center of Bragg's line, Federal troops under General Thomas smashed through Confederate positions at the base of the ridge, sweeping up the hill and driving Bragg's men before them.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] With his army disintegrating before his eyes, Bragg ordered Cleburne to hold the Federals off long enough to let the rest of his men escape.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The 33rd Alabama attacked approaching skirmishers in the gathering darkness, allowing the remainder of Bragg's army to cross Chickamauga Creek to the east and retreat into Georgia.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Since his division had held more-or-less together during the rout, Cleburne now found his regiments—including the 33rd Alabama—serving as the rearguard of the Army of Tennessee.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] As his army continued to retreat, General Bragg became concerned by the deep mud slowing his supply trains as he passed through the mountains near the town of Ringgold.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] As the rest of their division moved on the next day, the 33rd was left with elements of the 45th Alabama and some of Joseph Wheeler's cavalry to guard the creek against the oncoming Federals.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Advance Federal elements skirmished with them as the 33rd and Wheeler's Cavalry slowly backtracked toward Ringgold Gap, turning several times to fire, retreating a short distance, then turning to fire again.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Meanwhile, in the gap itself, Cleburne deployed his division in the face of the oncoming Federals.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] With barely 4,000 men and only two cannon to hold off Joseph Hooker's 16,000 attacking troops, Cleburne arranged his troops across both sides of the narrow pass, ordering them to conceal themselves from view and wait for his signal.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Thirty minutes later the 33rd and their friends finally backed into the gap; Matthews reports that the other regiments had done such a good job of concealing themselves that he and his friends never noticed them until they had passed their positions.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The 33rd was ordered to take its place with the rest of their brigade in the center atop White Oak Ridge, on the pass's northern side.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] When Hooker's lead elements entered the mountain pass, Cleburne allowed them to get to within fifty yards of his men before ordering them to open fire.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Reeling from the first volleys, the astonished Federals fell back, but quickly regrouped and mounted one furious counterattack after another, seeking first to turn Cleburne's right flank (where the 33rd Alabama was), then his left.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Each renewed assault ran into a withering Confederate response, described by one history as "a wall of fire;" one of Cleburne's regiments exhausted its ammunition, and resorted to throwing rocks before the reserve came up and relieved them.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] From the foot to the top of the hill was covered with the slain, all lying on their faces ...
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The ground was piled with dead Yankees; they were lying in heaps." Once his columns had reached safety further south in Dalton, Bragg ordered Cleburne to pull back; he withdrew his men, and Hooker took possession of the pass around 2 PM.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] In the midst of all the carnage, the 33rd Alabama had lost only one man; their division as a whole had lost only twenty killed and 201 wounded, while holding off a Federal force four times their number for nearly five hours.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] At Ringgold Gap, Cleburne and his men became the stuff of legend; the entire division received the Thanks of the Confederate Congress for their performance at this engagement.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] But the war was far from over, as the Alabamians and their friends soon learned.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Having safely withdrawn to Dalton, Georgia, General Bragg directed Cleburne to camp at nearby Tunnel Hill, a town bearing the same name as the spot he had defended atop Missionary Ridge.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Private Matthews reports that the 33rd Alabama was given "some cabins ... above the tunnel ... some were of round oak poles, others of split oak log, their cracks daubed with clay." Captured shelter halves were used as doors, and the men wintered there as best they could.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Not everyone in the camp had the best interests of their comrades at heart: "two or more sharpers," said he, accosted soldiers doing various chores and seek to con them out of their earnings.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] One regiment was assigned to guard duty every day; whenever the 33rd Alabama drew this duty, they packed up their gear and marched a mile or so to the front lines, leaving behind their sick and a guard over their other property.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] On December 2, 1863, The 33rd Alabama and their comrades in the Army of Tennessee learned that they were getting a new commander: Braxton Bragg, who had led the army since the Kentucky Campaign, had resigned his position.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] General Hardee was given temporary charge of the force, but on December 27 General Joseph Johnston, a veteran leader who proved popular with many of his troops, took command.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] With Chattanooga safe and the Confederates retreating, General Grant sent Sherman to Mississippi, against the Confederate rail center in Meridian.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Learning of this move, Johnston ordered two divisions of his army, including Cleburne's, to go to the aid of their compatriots in that state.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] This, in turn, led General Thomas to launch a series of probing attacks along Johnston's lines at Dalton, where he quickly learned that the new Confederate commander was someone to be reckoned with.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The 33rd Alabama had proceeded as far as West Point, Alabama, when they were recalled to Dalton.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Instead of returning to Tunnel Hill, they were ordered into camp along a creek east of town, where they were put to work digging trenches between that point and their old campsite on the hill.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Rifle practices were held, with targets set up at various distances up to two-hundred yards, and a "sham battle" was fought using blank cartridges.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] West of Dalton, Johnston entrenched a large portion of his army along the crest of Rocky Face Ridge, a rugged mountain extending north-to-south that was pierced by passes at Buzzard Roost Gap, Dug Gap and Snake Creek Gap.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Sherman had returned to Georgia after winning a victory at Meridian; here he was given command of a new Federal force known as the Military Division of the Mississippi, consisting of three armies totaling 98,500 men.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Johnston, for his part, had 50,000 men at this time.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] When part of Sherman's army passed through undefended Snake Creek Gap toward Resaca in the Confederate rear, the 33rd Alabama and other units were sent to stop them.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Ordered to assault a height near the gap, the 33rd drove the Federals from the ridge, then drove off fierce counterattacks throughout the day.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Some soldiers threw rocks at their enemies, while others pried large boulders loose and rolled them down the hill onto the attacking Northerners, who finally withdrew.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] All these efforts went for naught, however, as Sherman ultimately flanked the "Georgia Gibraltar" and forced Johnston to withdraw toward Resaca.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Following their retreat from Rocky Face Ridge, Johnston's Army of Tennessee engaged in a war of fight-and-get-flanked, in which Johnston first dug in at some defensible location, whereupon Sherman launched diversionary attacks on his smaller force, while flanking the Confederates elsewhere.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] At Resaca the 33rd Alabama was deployed with the rest of Hardee's Corps along Camp Creek, northwest of town; a series of Federal attacks on their lines were largely repulsed, until Sherman was able to flank Johnston and force him to retreat yet again.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Additional battles at Adairsville and New Hope—though the latter was a Confederate victory—did nothing to change the strategic situation, as Sherman inched closer and closer to Atlanta.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Moving into the Dallas area on May 26, the Federals attacked Johnston's right flank at Pickett's Mill on May 27.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Determined to outflank Johnston's latest defensive position in the Allatoona Pass, Sherman moved to the southwest, intending to circle around Allatoona and cut off Johnston's retreat.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] But Johnston beat him to the punch, pulling back and moving toward Dallas.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Opposite them were three Federal divisions belonging to Major Generals Thomas J.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Hascall; the overall plan was for Sherman's army to attack the Confederate right flank.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] For this fight, the 33rd mustered 525 men present for duty, with the number of "effectives" rated at 493.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The battle began at 7:00 am, when Cleburne sent Govan's Arkansas Brigade forward in a reconnaissance in force against the Federal left flank.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Haskell's men quickly engaged the Southerners, while other Federal forces prepared to counterattack.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Just as Cleburne ordered Govan's men to return to their original lines, they were attacked by two Federal divisions led by General Oliver O.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Howard, who had swung out beyond the Federal left flank, seeking to turn the Confederate right.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Cleburne extended his division in that direction toward a wheatfield; he also ordered his pioneers to rapidly construct trails to facilitate movement of men and supplies between his brigades.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Incredibly, the Federal commander, General Howard, only ordered a single brigade to attack, even though six were available to him.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] This unit quickly became separated amid thick underbrush and rugged terrain, with catastrophic results.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Additional Federal units were eventually sent forward, but since they got no support from other units on their line, Cleyburne was free to order Lowrey's Brigade—including the 33rd Alabama—to move to Govan's assistance.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Lowrey's men arrived around 5:30, with the 33rd in the lead.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Each regiment was ordered to clear the one in front of it, then turn left and come onto line.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Kelly now came up, and ordered two Arkansas regiments to the left of the 33rd to charge the Federals; the 33rd Alabama chose to charge with them, with seven companies accompanying the Arkansas troops, and the other four veering off into a wooded hollow to the right.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The Federals (belonging to the 5th Kentucky) attempted to regroup, but were hit by the 33rd's four right companies, who engaged them briefly in a cornfield before retreating to the safety of the woods, where they continued to fire on the Federals.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] General Lowrey arrived at this time, personally rallying the 33rd by riding back and forth among them on his horse 'Rebel' as the battle raged around him.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The Federals broke and ran, then regrouped, with both sides continuing to blaze away at each other across the cornfield in the gathering twilight.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Around 10:00 pm, a night charge by a nearby Confederate brigade under Hiram B.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Granbury pushed the Northerners back, causing other Federal units to withdraw and giving the Confederates a victory at Pickett's Mill.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Their win went for naught, though, as Sherman simply moved around the Southerners, heading for Marietta.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Here he dislodged Johnston once again, as the two-to-one advantage in Federal numbers and their greater firepower proved too much for Johnston to resist.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] By late June 1864, Sherman and Johnston were dancing a strange ballet of attack and maneuver, but the Federal commander abruptly decided to try something new.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] In later years Sherman indicated that his officers and opponents had become used to his propensity for flanking movements; he wanted to shake things up, he said, and demonstrate that he was capable of different tactics if a favorable opportunity arose.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] With rain and mud rendering movement difficult, Sherman decided to assault Johnston head-on at Kennesaw Mountain, a 1,808-foot ridge that dominated the surrounding countryside—including the railroad on which he depended for supplies.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Johnston had constructed miles of trenches and fortifications on Kennesaw and nearby hills; Cleburne's Division was ordered to take a position in the center of the Confederate line.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] As it turned out, the main Federal attack came in Cleburne's direction.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The 33rd Alabama, with the rest of Lowrey's brigade, was deployed to the right side of Cheatham Hill, facing two Federal divisions led by Jefferson C.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Davis and John Newton—around 8,000 men in all.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Newton attacked the sector held by the 33rd, which lay across a shallow creek situated in a valley about twenty feet deep that gave way to sloping ground, all of which was densely forested and covered with thick underbrush that made a proper pre-attack reconnaissance impossible.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Felled trees and sharpened stakes driven into the ground complicated the Federal attack, which kicked off with an artillery barrage around 8:00 am on June 27.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Though the Northerners managed to make some progress at first, ferocious fire from the 33rd and the rest of their compatriots drove the Federals back.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Having lost 3,000 casualties to the Southerners' 1,000, Sherman finally called off the assault and left the field to his foes; a few days later he flanked Johnston once more, causing the Confederates to withdraw yet again and leading to Johnston's dismissal by Jefferson Davis on July 17.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The new commander of the Army of Tennessee was John Bell Hood, a hard-charging general who had spent part of the war serving under Longstreet in Lee's Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Although he had demonstrated great personal bravery numerous times on the battlefield and was regarded as one of the best brigade and division commanders in the entire Confederate Army, Hood's former boss seems to have questioned his fitness for this level of command.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] After taking command of the Army of Tennessee, General Hood immediately attacked Sherman in a series of spectacular but ill-advised assaults that ultimately sealed his fate at Atlanta.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The first of these came at Peachtree Creek, where the 33rd Alabama was held in reserve and played no role in the contest.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Hood's men were initially successful, but miscommunication and fierce Federal counterattacks finally turned the tide in Sherman's favor, and the Army of Tennessee was forced back into their fortifications around the city.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] One day after Peachtree Creek the 33rd Alabama lost its regimental commander, Colonel Samuel Adams, who had been with it from its inception.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Walking along the front line early that morning inspecting his men, Adams was shot by a Federal sharpshooter; he sat down by a small oak tree with both hands over his heart, and died there.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Lieutenant Colonel Robert Crittenden took command of the regiment that same day.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Despising Sherman's overwhelming numbers and determined to renew his offensive, General Hood decided to attack James B.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] McPherson's Army of the Tennessee (not to be confused with Hood's own Army of Tennessee).
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] When one Lieutenant in the regiment realized that the captured Federal ambulance contained a 10-gallon keg of whiskey, he immediately sent soldiers back to guard it until it could be safely removed.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Once the 33rd had finished fortifying its position, the whiskey was doled out at the rate of one gill per man, measured in a tin cup.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] During the Siege of Atlanta, members of the 33rd quickly learned that they were safer below ground than above it.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] At first they slept on the ground just behind their trenches, but with snipers and artillery wreaking havoc among them at night, they decided to stay in their ditch at all times.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Perpendicular trenches were dug to grant access to their rear areas, while lights of any kind were banned at night.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] With no means of washing their clothes, the men suffered from insect infestations; their agony was compounded by a nearby Federal gun that managed to draw a transverse bead on their trench, doing considerable damage until Confederate counter-battery fire finally silenced it.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The regiment was gradually moved to the left each day, digging new ditches in the red clay soil with bayonets, spades or picks, but never engaging the enemy.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] On the night of August 30, the 33rd Alabama was ordered to move to its left, with its troops collapsing from exhaustion every time the regiment stopped to rest.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Arriving in the Atlanta suburb of Jonesborough on the morning of the 31st, the 33rd was fed into the line and permitted to rest for a time.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] In the afternoon they and the rest of Lowery's Brigade were ordered to charge the Federal works, where they managed to capture two steel cannon.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] They were quickly ambushed by dismounted Union cavalry commanded by Hugh Judson Kilpatrick and armed with Spencer Repeating Rifles; the brigade managed to drive them back, but were soon stopped by other Federal troops and returned to their lines.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] On September 1, Cleburne's division was attacked by elements of two Federal corps.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Private Matthews reports that the Federals nearly broke their line, only to be driven back with the help of reinforcements from General Cheatham's division.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] These men were later withdrawn to bolster up another section of the line, however, leaving the 33rd to defend its sector with a single line of troops and no reserve.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Further Federal attacks did not materialize; the Northerners were content to snipe at the 33rd throughout the rest of the day while their compatriots smashed through the Confederate line further north, leading the remnants to withdraw around nine that evening.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Members of the regiment could see fires and hear explosions on the horizon, as Hood destroyed all of his supplies in Atlanta and evacuated the city.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The Alabamians linked up with an ambulance carrying their wounded and followed it to Lovejoy, Georgia, where they repulsed a Federal attack on the railroad there and got the first real night's sleep they had enjoyed in 122 days.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] After his defeat at Atlanta, General Hood regrouped his army at Lovejoy's Station, following which he moved to Palmetto, Georgia.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Here the Army of Tennessee was reviewed by Confederate President Jefferson Davis, who had come to speak with Hood about his next move.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Even after the debacle at Atlanta, Hood still retained a formidable force of 39,000 men, and though Davis expressed disappointment in the way he had fought in Georgia and spoke of relieving him from command, he ultimately decided that Hood would keep his job.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Davis did order Lieutenant General Hardee, the 33rd's longtime corps commander, to a new assignment, replacing him with Frank Cheatham.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Hoping to draw Sherman away from Atlanta, Hood and Davis decided that the Army of Tennessee would move north toward Chattanooga, seeking to damage Federal supply lines and force Sherman to do battle on terrain favorable to the Confederates.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] By October 3, 1864, the Army of Tennessee had reached Kennesaw, site of their battle earlier that summer.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] So far, Hood's plan seemed to be working: Sherman had sent General Thomas back to Nashville to organize troops in that state, while sending another division under Brigadier General James Morgan to Chattanooga.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Federal cavalry assigned to follow Hood's army lost track of him periodically and were only able to give an approximate picture of his movements.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The 33rd camped near Lost Mountain on the third, on an old battlefield where the Confederate dead had been buried in shallow graves or simply left to rot.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Private Matthews reported seeing decaying hands, feet or limbs protruding from the dirt, where dogs and other scavengers had dug up the graves to get at the rotting food in their haversacks.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] After spending a day reburying the exposed corpses, the 33rd moved on to Dallas and then to Cedartown, where one man in the regiment was killed in a freak accident after lightning struck a stack of rifles he was hanging his haversack on.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Turning northeast toward Dalton, the regiment tore up railroad tracks along Sherman's supply line by heating the rails atop a fire made of railroad ties, then bending them.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Men from the regiment were beginning to recognize old battlefields and campsites; on one night near Lafayette, the regiment even camped in the exact spot it had occupied just before the Battle of Chickamauga, the year before.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Bypassing a strong Federal garrison at Resaca, Hood turned southwest and headed into Alabama, toward George Thomas' army headquartered in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] For the first time in the war the 33rd would be operating inside its native state, if only briefly.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Sherman had turned back toward Atlanta, from whence he would begin his famed March to the Sea, after sending additional troops to help Thomas in Tennessee.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Hood's plan was to drive north into Tennessee, defeat Thomas there, then move into Kentucky and thence east into Virginia, where Robert E.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Seeking to link up with reinforcements under famed cavalry General Nathan Bedford Forrest, Hood moved west through northern Alabama to Florence, then north into Tennessee.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] At first, Generals Thomas and Sherman did not believe that Hood would actually invade Tennessee, with a Federal army about to burn its way through Georgia.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] However, as it became clear that this was Hood's destination, Thomas began to take action.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Schofield to move to Columbia on the Duck River, Thomas hoped to intercept Hood before he could seize this important crossing.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Hood split his army into three columns: the 33rd and the rest of Cheatham's Corps marched in the westernmost one through seventy miles of freezing rain, sleet and bitterly cold winds toward Mt.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Pleasant, where the three columns reunited and continued in the direction of Columbia.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Effectively screened by Forrest's cavalry, the Confederates reached Columbia just after the Federals had arrived and started to entrench.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Amazingly, neither side reported any casualties in this encounter, which had consisted almost entirely of feints and shelling.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Having moved around Schofield's rapidly retreating force, Hood hoped to catch and destroy it near Spring Hill, to the north of Columbia.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The Army of Tennessee moved rapidly along back-country roads and through fields and woods, with the men required to keep in ranks at all times while stragglers were dealt with severely.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Forrest's cavalry arrived at the crossroads around 11:30 am on November 29; there they ran into elements of the Federal IV Corps, which had rushed ahead to hold the crossing until the rest of Schofield's army could arrive.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Cleburne's division arrived in the afternoon just as Forrest's men were about to exhaust their ammunition.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] They immediately deployed for an attack, with the 33rd Alabama crossing a small stream and advancing around 4:00 pm with the rest of their division toward a Federal brigade under the command of Colonel Luther Prentice Bradley.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Cleburne staggered his brigades in echelon formation, with Lowrey's Brigade on the far right.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Here they were stopped cold by Federal artillery; as darkness fell, the entire Confederate attack ground to a halt.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Although Hood planned to attack Schofield's approaching army in the morning, the Federals slipped by him in the darkness while he and his men slept, moving on to the nearby town of Franklin.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Here the 33rd and the rest of Hood's army were about to experience their worst day of the war.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] On November 30, 1864, General Hood awoke to learn that Schofield's army had slipped by him during the night and was now safely entrenched in Franklin, 12 miles (19 km) to the north.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Enraged at this unexpected development, Hood angrily blamed his subordinates—especially Cheatham—for letting the Federals escape.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Determined to stop Schofield from uniting with Thomas' main force at Nashville, Hood resolved to attack him head-on at Franklin, even though the Federals were now behind formidable fortifications (built for a previous battle fought there the year before).
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] These included breastworks six-to-eight feet high fronted by four-foot wide ditches, and thorny obstructions using branches from Osage Orange trees in the area.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Although Hood had roughly 39,000 men, only 27,000 would make the attack; this placed them at even odds with the Federals, who had the same number of men.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Hood's army began to arrive at Franklin around 1:00 pm, with the infantry far outpacing their artillery and other support personnel.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Rather than wait for his guns to come up, Hood ordered an immediate assault, as the sun would be setting in just over three and a half hours and he did not want Schofield to get away again.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Cleburne, Cheatham and Forrest all protested Hood's plan, but their commander remained determined.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] So, bereft of artillery support, Cleburne now prepared to lead his division across two miles of open field toward the very center of the Federal line.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] During the attack at Franklin, Lowrey's Brigade formed a second line in Cleburne's division, behind the brigades of Govan and Granbury.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Moving through savage cannon fire toward the Carter House Cotton Gin across the field, the 33rd halted briefly with their sister regiments to fix bayonets, having been ordered not to shoot until they reached the Federal trenches.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Then screaming their famous "rebel yell" they charged headlong into the breastworks, held in this sector by the 100th and 104th Ohio Infantryi regiments, the 6th Ohio Battery and Battery A of the 1st Kentucky.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Behind them stood the 16th Kentucky, the 12th Kentucky, the 8th Tennessee (Union) Infantry, and Battery "A" of the 1st Ohio Battery.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Behind *them* was the 175th Ohio Infantry.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Two privates of the 33rd left accounts of what happened next.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The final charge of Patrick Cleburne and his men at Franklin has been featured in Civil War art.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Some examples of this include portraits by Dale Gallon, Don Troiani and Mort Kunstler.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] By the time the smoke cleared at Franklin, the Army of Tennessee had suffered a cataclysmic defeat: it had lost 6,252 men in just a couple of hours, including six dead generals, six wounded, and one captured.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] In addition, 55 of Hood's regimental commanders became casualties—an appalling loss of mid-level commanders in an army that had lost many, already.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The 33rd Alabama lost two-thirds of its original 285 men; the remnant could no longer function as an independent fighting unit, so they were consolidated with survivors from the 16th and 45th Alabama regiments in a single formation, though the regimental designations were not rescinded.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Incredibly, even after his debacle at Franklin, General Hood insisted on continuing his march toward Nashville.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] He seems to have been motivated more by a desire to prevent his army from disintegrating through desertion than by any thought that he stood a chance of victory, now that Thomas had 71,842 men to his 23,053.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Federal engineers had been fortifying the city for over two years; in addition to seven miles of trench lines and fortifications, a powerful fleet of Union ironclads on the Cumberland River offered additional firepower while protecting the city from amphibious assault.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Hood arrived at Nashville on December 2 and set to work constructing his own line of fortifications, hoping that Thomas would emerge from behind his own breastworks and attack him under unfavorable conditions.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Cheatham's corps, including the badly depleted 33rd Alabama, manned the right section of Hood's line.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Lowrey's Brigade held the extreme right flank, which ended at a deep railroad cut belonging to the Nashville and Chattanooga Railroad.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] A bitter ice storm began on December 8 and subzero temperatures persisted through December 12, further complicating the Southerners' misery.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Hood did not have to wait long for his nemesis to appear: once the weather abated, Thomas emerged from his fortifications on December 15, and hit Hood's army.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The Federal attack smashed Hood's left, and he was compelled to retreat to a new and more compact line, some distance to the rear of his original line.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The following morning found the 33rd Alabama with the rest of Cheatham's Division on the Confederate left flank, near a road called the Granny White Pike.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] This section of the front was hit late in the day by a three-brigade attack led by Federal Brigadier General John McArthur, which smashed through the poorly placed defenses and rolled up Hood's line from west to east as additional Union forces joined the assault.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Hood's army rapidly disintegrated, with its shattered remnants fleeing down the Granny White Pike and nearby roads to Columbia, not ultimately stopping until they reached Tupelo, Mississippi, 220 miles away.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Already decimated by its fruitless assault at Franklin, the once-proud Army of Tennessee was all but obliterated at Nashville.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Having taken 39,000 men with him into Tennessee the month before, Hood came out with 18,742.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] His own career irreparably ruined, Hood resigned his position and would not receive another command for the duration of the war.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Following the disaster at Nashville, the few remaining members of the 33rd Alabama withdrew with the rest of their shattered army, first to Columbia, then further south to Decatur, Alabama, and thence to Tupelo.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Morale had sunk to an all-time low, with many of the survivors believing they had been "unfortunately handled." In January 1865 the regiment drew shoes and marched from Tupelo to West Point, Mississippi, where they boarded a train that took them first to Meridian and then to Demopolis, Alabama.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Here they were forced to sleep in the mud along the tracks, because they could find no branches to make ridge-poles for their tents.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] On the way to Selma the following day, their train derailed in an eerie repeat of the episode in late 1862; several men from Companies B and G were sitting on top of the cars, and were injured when their boxcars left the tracks.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The men dusted themselves off and resumed their journey, arriving in Selma the next day, where they boarded steamboats and proceeded to Montgomery.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Here their final assignment awaited them, in Joseph Johnston's newly formed Army of the South.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The regiment participated at the three-day Battle of Bentonville on March 19–21, 1865, not arriving on the battlefield until the final day when the contest was already lost.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] On April 8 they, along with the 16th and 45th Alabama, were consolidated with the 17th Alabama; this remnant was surrendered to General Sherman with the rest of Johnston's army at Bennett Place near Durham eighteen days later.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] Sherman issued ten day's rations to his former enemies, then released them to return to their homes.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] On his way back to Alabama, Private Matthews reported that Federal soldiers assigned to guard the trains took pleasure in shooting at livestock from the moving boxcars.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p02] The regimental survivors returned to their homes in southeastern Alabama, where some resumed their lives while others eventually relocated to different counties and states.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] The first regimental commander of the 33rd Alabama was Colonel Samuel Adams, born in 1829 in Abbeville, South Carolina.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Educated at South Carolina College (from which he graduated in 1850), he relocated to Greenville, Alabama, where he served as principal of an academy there.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] He spent his spare time reading Law, and was admitted to the Alabama Bar in 1852.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] He married Dora Herbert, and soon embarked on a political career, being elected to the U.S House of Representatives from the Whig Party in 1857 and 1859.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Adams initially enlisted in the 9th Alabama Infantry in 1861, where he was elected first lieutenant of his company and served in the Confederate Army of the Potomac, the antecedent of Robert E.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Released in February 1862 to recruit men in his home state, he was chosen to command the newly formed 33rd Alabama.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Adams was wounded in the foot at Perryville while leading a brigade; after returning to regimental command in 1864, he was awaiting a recommended promotion to brigadier general when he was mortally wounded by a Federal sharpshooter at the Battle of Atlanta.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] After Perryville Adams was replaced by Colonel Robert Crittenden of Coffee County, who was captured at Nashville.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Other regimental officers included: Isaac Corn, James Dunklin, John Crosby, A.N.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Adams and Moore were killed in battle, Crosby died of natural causes, Dunklin was wounded, and Crittenden was captured.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] The first regimental flag of the 33rd Alabama was described as: "blue, with a white crescent moon near the center, trimmed with a two-inch white border;" later versions incorporated the regimental number and battles in which it had participated.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Cleburne's division especially nursed a rivalry with the division led by Major General Benjamin F.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Cheatham; the two often fought side by side, and while good-natured competitiveness ran high between them, so did mutual camaraderie and trust.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] The colors of the 33rd Alabama were captured at Franklin by Captain J.H.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Brown of Company D, 12th Kentucky Infantry Regiment.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Unlike other captured Confederate flags, which were displayed for decades in Northern public places or elsewhere, the flag of the 33rd vanished soon after being given the designation "Flag No.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] In 1940, it was rediscovered by accident at an estate sale in Melrose, Massachusetts.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Citizens of the town joined with local public figures to purchase the flag, which was presented to the Governor of Alabama during a special ceremony in September of that year.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] The flag was given to the state archives, where it has been treated to aid in its preservation, and is now on exhibit in their museum.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] A replacement for the captured regimental standard was made soon after its loss at Franklin; this was described as a "Hardee-pattern battle flag with no numbers, words or battle honors." This banner was kept by Captain Needham Hughes of Co.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] I, who was acting as the 33rd's brigade commander at the close of the war.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] He slipped out of the regiment's camp just after the capitulation and wrapped the flag around himself, under his uniform, to prevent it from being turned over to the Union authorities as a trophy of war.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Hughes took it home, and it has been in his family ever since.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Matthews,a a Private in the 33rd Alabama's Company B, left an extremely detailed description of the equipment issued to his regiment by Confederate and state authorities.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Later, in October 1862, the regiment drew new uniforms upon their return to Knoxville, Tennessee, after the disastrous Kentucky Campaign.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] These were initially soaked in water and then worn; some men had to wear two completely different sized shoes, one for each foot.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] These rifles were later replaced by Enfields, which were in turn subsequently discarded for captured Federal Springfield rifles, which were seen as more dependable.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Writing about knapsacks, canteens and other gear issued during their initial deployment to Ft.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Rations issued to the men of the 33rd varied, depending on the time and location.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Speaking of the regiment's fare during their early days at Ft.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] In Tullahoma, Tennessee, in early 1863, regimental rations now consisted largely of fresh pork; after the hogs had been butchered, their intestines would be left for any soldiers who wished to make chitterlings out of them.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Salt (which Matthews says was carried in "small cloth wallets in our haversacks") and coffee were highly prized, with "ghouls" even taking them from the dead.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] He also mentions "flour, corn meal, rice, some fresh beef, some sweet and Irish potatoes ... and soap" being issued at this time.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] While in the field, rations for the 33rd (and other Confederate regiments) were usually cooked at a site located two to five miles in the rear area behind the front lines, where the "regimental skillet wagon" was located.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Men were periodically assigned to KP duty here, where they chopped wood, carried water and cooked meals.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] A regimental teamster was assigned to draw rations daily from the nearest railhead; in May 1864 these consisted of one pound of unbolted corn per man per day, or the same weight of flour made of wheat and cowpeas ground together.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] In addition, each soldier was allotted a half-pound of bacon, or a pound of fresh beef.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] When this arrangement proved impractical (such as during combat), uncooked rations were issued, and each soldier was on their own.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Unlike modern armies who employ trained cooks, the 33rd made do with troops from the ranks; the quality of their preparations accordingly varied, with Matthews reporting of one cook: "Co.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Local farmers had fled the area, leaving their fields unplanted and their stock scattered or dead.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] While cornbread, biscuits and beef were occasionally issued in minute quantities, persimmons were often the only food the 33rd got to eat on a regular basis.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] On their final journey from Mississippi to North Carolina in early 1865, the 33rd drew two-days' worth of rations described as: "three-fourths pound of corn meal and a half pound of flour, and three-fourths pound beef and one-third pound of bacon," plus sweet potatoes.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Various sundries were available at different times to men of the 33rd.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Other soldiers would gather around "in droves" with twigs, bark and other kindling to ignite and carry back to start their own blazes.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] By April 1863, groundpeas retailed at 25 cents per "short tin quart;" stick candy was five cents per stick or $3.50 for a five-pound bundle; coffee was $5 per pound, and corn whiskey sold at varying prices, depending on availability.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] A local farmer who had received supplies from a Blockade runner might sell it for $1.00 per quart, or twenty-five cents per glass—usually only to those who belonged to a club.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] During the Siege of Chattanooga, Matthews says that liver could be bought at 75 cents per pound; a cow's head cost 50 cents to a dollar per pound, while the tongue cost 75 cents to a dollar.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] A dollar could also buy a short pint of cowpeas, salt or rice.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] For a short time the regiment had the services of some women who sold a "very small hot biscuit, without yeast or shortening, and with very little salt in them" for a dollar, as well.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Two men in the regiment specialized in baking cakes of flour, black sorghum syrup and a little salt, which were sold by sutlers during the regiment's time at Atlanta.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] These fetched a dollar apiece, or ten for $9.00, or $66.65 per hundred.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Purchasers learned not to eat these while marching, as two men who did were later sent to the rear in an ambulance.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Civil War was often administered with great severity.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] On another occasion, regimental soldiers were called out to witness the executions of two men: one had deserted, and the other was convicted of raping women.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] On this occasion, however, a last-minute reprieve from the army commander stopped both executions.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Discipline within the 33rd Alabama was lenient, compared to this.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Most minor offenses were dealt with initially by a warning; if the conduct persisted, the offender might be given extra "police duty," which would entail sweeping, cleaning his living area, digging or cleaning out latrine or offal pits or similar activities during off-duty hours.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] The worst punishment usually meted out for all but the most serious of offenses was to be confined to the guard quarters while performing extra duty; however, Matthews indicates that those so confined were often helped in doing their punishment work by comrades who felt sorry for them.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] The worst punishments inflicted on anyone in the 33rd were "bucking and gagging,"f the wearing of a "barrel shirt,"f or carrying a rail while marching.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] According to Matthews, this was done to just one man—and that by the army's provost marshal, not any regimental authority.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Field hygiene and sanitation are extremely important in the prevention of disease, which was responsible for two-thirds of the deaths suffered during the Civil War.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Matthews reports that when a member of Company B accidentally dropped his pocketwatch into the latrine pit one morning, he paid a black cook $5.00 to get it out.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Often food and clothing would be sent to the regiment from families back home, in care of a soldier returning from furlough.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Private Matthews writes that such a man would have to remain with them on the boxcars even after his leave had expired, to prevent them from being stolen.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] One such man was AWOL for two weeks while keeping an eye on some boxes shipped by families of soldiers from Eufaula, but when he was finally able to obtain transportation for himself and his cargo to the regiment, he was absolved of all charges and nothing further was said.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Giving nicknames to soldiers has long been a feature of military life.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] Private David McCook of Company B was referred to as the "Skillet Wagon" by men of other companies, because they were always borrowing his tin pans, buckets or cans for cooking.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] The 33rd Alabama Infantry has been featured in Civil War art.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/33rd-regiment-alabama-infantry-p03] 33rd Alabama Infantry – Modern re-enactment group.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-hall-of-fame] The **Alabama Hall of Fame** was established by Act of Alabama No.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-hall-of-fame] 646 (1951) to recognize "worthy citizens of the state who rendered outstanding service or who won fame on account of their achievements as to make them exceptional in the history of Alabama".
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-hall-of-fame] Its membership consists of people considered to be instrumental to the history of the state of Alabama, as selected by a nine-member board.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-hall-of-fame] The Hall of Fame plaques are located at the Alabama Department of Archives and History.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The **Alabama Museum of Natural History** is the official natural history museum of the state of Alabama, located in Smith Hall on the campus of the University of Alabama campus in Tuscaloosa.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] Established in 1831, it is the oldest museum in the state.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The exhibits depict the natural diversity of Alabama from the Age of Dinosaurs, the Coal Age, and the Ice Age.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] Collections include items relating to geology, zoology, mineralogy, paleontology, ethnology, history, and photography.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The Grand Gallery Exhibition Hall houses a replica of a *Basilosaurus cetoides*, an Eocene whale that has been designated as the State Fossil.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] Exhibits include the skull of an American mastodon dredged from the Tombigbee River near Demopolis and the Hodges meteorite.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The latter hit a woman as it fell to earth near Sylacauga on November 30, 1954.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The museum sponsors expeditions throughout the year, as it has since 1979.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The Alabama Museum of Natural History was established in 1831, when the University of Alabama began assembling natural history specimens for research and teaching.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The site of the Alabama Museum of Natural History, Smith Hall, is named for Eugene Allen Smith, who was appointed state geologist in 1873 and spent nearly forty years surveying, mapping and collecting scientific specimens throughout the state.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The cornerstone for Smith Hall was laid on May 28, 1907.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] Construction was completed in the autumn of 1909 and it was formally dedicated on May 5, 1910.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] Smith recruited collector Herbert Huntington Smith (no relation) as the museum's curator.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] Smith directed the Museum under Eugene Smith from 1910 till his death in 1919.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] Herbert Smith's wife, Amelia Woolworth Smith was also a collector and worked for the museum, and replaced her husband as acting curator after he died.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] Smith Hall consists of a three-story central block, built to house the Alabama Museum of Natural History, and adjoining two-story north and south wings.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The north wing originally housed the Department of Biology with the south wing housing the Department of Geology.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The Department of Geology currently occupies both wings.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The architecture of Smith Hall mirrors on a smaller scale the design and layout of several large natural history museums that were also built during the early years of the 20th century in Chicago, New York City, and Washington, D.C.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The building is designed in a Classical Revival style known as Beaux-Arts.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The exterior features an engaged colonnade of eight Ionic columns raised above a podium-like ground floor.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The main entrance is at ground level through a pedimented stone doorway.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] Immediately inside the entrance is a center hall dominated by a sweeping staircase made of Alabama marble and supported by Alabama-manufactured iron.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The staircase leads to the Grand Gallery Exhibition Hall on the second floor.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] The Grand Gallery is ringed by a colonnade of monumental Corinthian columns supporting an entablature and cornice.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alabama-museum-of-natural-history] A barrel vaulted ceiling above the cornice contains skylights that provide the space with natural light.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:eugene-allen-smith/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] He was born in the (now former) town of Washington, Alabama, in 1841, the son of Samuel Parrish Smith and his wife Adelaide Julia Allen.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] After an education in Prattville and a three-year stint at Central High School in Philadelphia, Eugene matriculated to the University of Alabama as a junior in 1860, where he graduated with an A.B. in 1862.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] With the American Civil War underway, Eugene enlisted as a private with the 33rd Regiment Alabama Infantry of the Confederate States Army, and was elected to the rank of 2nd lieutenant by the men.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] In December 1862, Eugene was appointed Instructor of Military Tactics at the University of Alabama by Jefferson Davis, president of the Confederate states.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] He remained in that post for the remainder of the war.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] In 1865 he entered graduate school at the University of Berlin, followed by further studies at the University of Göttingen, and finally spent two years at the University of Heidelberg, where he was awarded a Ph.D. in 1868.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] Smith joined the University of Mississippi faculty as an instructor of chemistry.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] In addition to his teaching duties, he served as assistant state geologist for Mississippi from 1868–1871.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] In 1871 he was named professor of geology at the rebuilding University of Alabama.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] On July 10, 1872 he married Jane Henry Meredith Garland; the couple had a son, Merrill Smith.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] Still on the staff of the University of Alabama, in 1873 Dr.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] He resumed a state geological survey that had been discontinued in 1857 with the death of Michael Tuomey, reporting on the mineral resources of Alabama.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] In 1878 he served as honorary commissioner for the state of Alabama to the Exposition Universelle in Paris, France.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] From 1884–1889 he served as a member of the American committee for the International Geological Congress.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] In 1904 he was a sectional vice president for the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] He was vice president for the Geological Society of America in 1906 and served as president in 1913.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] At the age of 86, he died at his home in Tuscaloosa eight days after surgery for a strangulated hernia.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] Smith had 116 publications in geological and scientific scholarly journals.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] Smith Hall on the University of Alabama campus is named after him; this building is now the Alabama Museum of Natural History.
[src:eugene-allen-smith/eugene-allen-smith] In 1953, he was made a member of the Alabama Hall of Fame.
